{"action": "edit", "code": "def pan_green_pixels(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> Tuple[np.ndarray, int]:\n    \"\"\"                                                                                                                                          \n    This function takes an input grid and pans the green pixels up or down many pixels until they are adjacent to the red pixels in the output_gr\n    It returns the output grid and the direction of the pan (1 for up and -1 for down).                                                          \n                                                                                                                                                 \n    Args:                                                                                                                                        \n    input_grid: A numpy array representing the input grid                                                                                        \n                                                                                                                                                 \n    Returns:                                                                                                                                     \n    A tuple containing the output grid and the direction of the pan (1 for up and -1 for down)                                                   \n    \"\"\"\n    output_grid = input_grid.copy()\n    direction = 1\n    green_pixels = np.where(output_grid == green)\n    red_pixels = np.where(output_grid == red)\n    if green_pixels[0][0] > red_pixels[0][0]:\n        direction = -1\n    while green_pixels[0][0] != red_pixels[0][0]:\n        output_grid = move_green_pixels(green_pixels, output_grid, direction)\n        green_pixels = np.where(output_grid == green)\n    return (output_grid, direction)\ndef fill_teal_rectangles(output_grid: np.ndarray, direction: int) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function takes an output grid and fills the other direction with teal rectangles that are adjacent to it.\n    \n    Args:\n    output_grid: A numpy array representing the output grid\n    direction: An integer representing the direction of the pan (1 for up and -1 for down)\n    \n    Returns:\n    A numpy array representing the output grid with teal rectangles filled in the other direction\n    \"\"\"\n    if direction == 1:\n        for i in range(output_grid.shape[0]):\n            if np.where(output_grid[i, :] == red)[0].size > 0:\n                output_grid[i + 1:i + 3, :] = teal\n                break\n    else:\n        for i in range(output_grid.shape[0] - 1, -1, -1):\n            if np.where(output_grid[i, :] == red)[0].size > 0:\n                output_grid[i - 2:i, :] = teal\n                break\n    return output_grid\ndef main(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    output_grid = input_grid.copy()\n    if input_grid.shape[0] > input_grid.shape[1]:\n        output_grid, direction = pan_green_pixels(output_grid)\n        output_grid = fill_teal_rectangles(output_grid, direction)\n    else:\n        output_grid, direction = pan_green_pixels_lr(output_grid)\n        output_grid = fill_teal_rectangles(output_grid, direction)\n    return output_grid\ndef pan_green_pixels_lr(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> Tuple[np.ndarray, int]:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function takes an input grid and pans the green pixels left or right many pixels until they are adjacent to the red pixels in the output_grid.\n    It returns the output grid and the direction of the pan (1 for left and -1 for right).\n    \n    Args:\n    input_grid: A numpy array representing the input grid\n    \n    Returns:\n    A tuple containing the output grid and the direction of the pan (1 for left and -1 for right)\n    \"\"\"\n    output_grid = input_grid.copy()\n    direction = 1\n    green_pixels = np.where(output_grid == green)\n    red_pixels = np.where(output_grid == red)\n    if green_pixels[1][0] > red_pixels[1][0]:\n        direction = -1\n    while green_pixels[1][0] != red_pixels[1][0]:\n        output_grid = np.roll(output_grid, direction, axis=1)\n        green_pixels = np.where(output_grid == green)\n    return (output_grid, direction)\ndef move_green_pixels(output_grid: np.ndarray, green_pixels: Tuple[np.ndarray, np.ndarray], direction: int) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"\n    This function takes an output grid, green pixels and direction and moves the green pixels one pixel in the output grid in the given direction.\n    \n    Args:\n    output_grid: A numpy array representing the output grid\n    green_pixels: A tuple containing two numpy arrays representing the row and column indices of the green pixels\n    direction: An integer representing the direction of the pan (1 for up or left and -1 for down or right)\n    \n    Returns:\n    A numpy array representing the output grid with green pixels moved one pixel in the given direction\n    \"\"\"\n    output_grid[green_pixels] = black\n    if direction == 1:\n        output_grid[green_pixels[0] - 1, green_pixels[1]] = green\n    else:\n        output_grid[green_pixels[0] + 1, green_pixels[1]] = green\n    return output_grid", "user_code": "def pan_green_pixels(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> Tuple[np.ndarray, int]:                                                                          \n    \"\"\"                                                                                                                                          \n    This function takes an input grid and pans the green pixels up or down many pixels until they are adjacent to the red pixels in the output_gr\n    It returns the output grid and the direction of the pan (1 for up and -1 for down).                                                          \n                                                                                                                                                 \n    Args:                                     